description: From Middle English inturnen, equivalent to in- +‎ turn.

verbs.description: inturn (third-person singular simple present inturns, present participle inturning, simple past and past participle inturned)

examples: A machine of the class described, comprising in combination with a suitably-actuated needle, a driving-shaft, means actuated from said shaft for carrying two or more plies of material through the machine, and similarly-actuated means working alternately with the needle to inturn the edges of said plies.

description: From Middle English inturn, intorn, equivalent to in- +‎ turn.

entries.meaning: The act or process of turning in.
(wrestling) A move where the wrestler puts his thigh between the tights of his opponent, and lifts him up.
